{:tx/id #hlc "1773951812/0/af86f4b0b23bbbe4de81fe20af03f998"
 :tx/agent "af86f4b0b23bbbe4de81fe20af03f998"
 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "DEEP DOG-FOOD REFLECTION — Session 027 experience report from the agent's perspective.\n\nWHAT WORKS BRILLIANTLY:\n\n1. braid next IS the killer feature. It told me exactly what to work on at every step. The R(t) routing consistently surfaced the highest-impact task. I never had to guess or scan a list. This is the single most valuable thing braid does — it eliminates the 'what should I work on?' question.\n\n2. braid go / braid task close create a natural work rhythm. Claim → implement → close → next. The ceremony is minimal (one command each) and the store captures the lifecycle. This is better than any external issue tracker because it's IN the conversation — I don't context-switch.\n\n3. braid observe captures insights that would otherwise be lost. The CRB auto-reconciliation is genuinely useful — when I observed the ACP design insight, it surfaced 3+ related spec elements I should check. This prevented me from duplicating existing work.\n\n4. braid task search solved a real pain point. Finding tasks by keyword across 300+ tasks was instant. Before this session, I had to use Datalog queries with keyword matching.\n\n5. The store as append-only truth. Every decision, every task, every observation — it's all in the store. When I needed to check if something was already done, I could query it. This is genuinely different from keeping notes in a file.\n\nWHAT CAUSES FRICTION:\n\n1. THE OUTPUT TRUNCATION (now fixed by ACP). This was the #1 pain point. Before ACP, every braid command was truncated at 50-300 tokens, often cutting off the most important part (the next action). I was working blind — running commands and getting garbled results. ACP fixed this, but the experience of working WITHOUT it for the first hour of the session was genuinely frustrating.\n\n2. Long task titles are still a problem. Even with the L1 title pyramid (≤80 chars), the task descriptions embedded in titles make everything noisy. The root cause: we put EVERYTHING in the title (BACKGROUND, ACCEPTANCE, APPROACH, FILE markers) because there's no good way to view the description field. A 'braid task show' should display the structured sections, but the title IS the description for most tasks.\n\n3. The guidance footer competes with ACP. Now that ACP puts the action first, the legacy footer at the bottom repeats similar information (M(t), next action) but in a different format. This is redundant — the footer should either be suppressed for ACP commands or unified completely.\n\n4. Schema evolution is invisible. I added 8 new schema attributes this session (:task/title-l0, :task/title-l1, :tx/reconciled, 5 :recon-source/* attrs) and got zero feedback. A 'braid schema --new' or a schema diff would help verify the attributes were installed.\n\n5. No way to see my session trajectory. I can see 'last session' in the seed, but I can't see 'what have I done in the CURRENT session?' A 'braid session summary' would help me track progress without harvesting.\n\n6. The harvest threshold is too aggressive. The system warned me about harvest being overdue after 15 transactions. But during a high-velocity implementation session, 15 transactions happen in 5 minutes. The warning became noise — I started ignoring it. The velocity-adaptive threshold (INV-GUIDANCE-019) would fix this but isn't fully wired.\n\nWHAT I WOULD IMPROVE (PRIORITIZED):\n\nP0: Task title/description separation. Create tasks with short titles and put the BACKGROUND/ACCEPTANCE/APPROACH in :task/description. The create CLI should support --body or stdin for the description. This would make every task list 10x more readable.\n\nP1: Session summary command. 'braid session summary' showing: tasks created, tasks closed, observations made, transactions, F(S) delta since session start. Without this, I have to harvest to see my progress.\n\nP1: Unified ACP + footer. The legacy footer should be fully replaced by ACP methodology context blocks for converted commands. Currently they coexist, which is redundant.\n\nP2: Schema diff. 'braid schema --diff' showing attributes added since a given transaction.\n\nP2: Harvest threshold tuning. The 15-tx threshold should adapt to velocity per INV-GUIDANCE-019.\n\nOVERALL ASSESSMENT:\n\nBraid is GENUINELY USEFUL for agentic work. The task management (next → go → close) + observation capture (observe) + session continuity (seed → harvest) form a real workflow that I followed naturally. The ACP innovation is the right architectural direction — action-first output is dramatically better than content-first truncated output.\n\nThe system is at an inflection point: the core abstractions (datom store, task management, guidance routing, bilateral coherence, ACP projection) are all sound and working. The friction points are UX-level issues (title length, schema visibility, footer redundancy) not architectural problems.\n\nThe biggest gap is between what braid CAN do and what the agent ACTUALLY DOES. I followed the methodology (observe → task → execute) most of the time, but under time pressure I skipped observations and went straight to implementation. The system detected this (M(t) dropped) but couldn't prevent it. This is the basin competition problem (ADR-GUIDANCE-002) in action — and it's the hardest problem to solve because it requires the agent to WANT to follow the methodology, not just be reminded to."
